The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Monday, May 17, 2004  LOOSE CHANGE
																								Templeton Mutual Fund has revised the load structure for Templeton Floating Rate Income  Long Term Plan. Now the fund will charge an exit load of 0.30 per cent for invest ment amount up to Rs 10 lakh, if redeemed within six months. 																								United Bank of India has reduced rates on its education loans up to Rs 2 lakh to 9 per cent. Interest rates on loans above Rs 2 lakh and up to Rs 4 lakh would be 9.5 per cent and for loans above that, the rate would be 10 per cent. A concession of 0.5 per cent will be allowed if the loan is repaid during the study period. 																								Benchmark Mutual Fund has unveiled Split Capital Fund, a five-year close-ended scheme. The fund will allot two classes of units. Preferred units class A will have priority for redemption, a finite maturity value and will be rated AAA (IND) (SO), while subordinated units Class B will get the residual return and will take hit first in case of default. Minimum investment is Rs 1,00,000 and the face value of the unit is Rs 1,000. The issue is open till May 26, 2004. 																								Reliance Mutual Fund has launched an open-ended pharma sector scheme which will invest in equity or equity related or fixed income securities of pharma and other associated companies. The minimum application amount is Rs 10,000 and the issue will remain open till May 26.
